Here's a simple A-Frame VR scene that simulates a city cafe. The scene includes navigation using the arrow keys and features 10 signs in French, German, and Swahili. You can copy and paste the following code into a single HTML file and open it in a web browser that supports WebVR.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>City Cafe VR</title>
    <script src="https://aframe.io/releases/1.2.0/aframe.min.js"></script>
    <style>
        body { margin: 0; }
        a-scene { height: 100vh; }
        .sign {
            color: white;
            font-size: 1.5em;
            text-align: center;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <a-scene>
        <a-sky color="#87CEEB"></a-sky>

        <a-box position="-2 0.5 -5" depth="0.1" height="1" width="2" color="#8B4513"></a-box>
        <a-box position="2 0.5 -5" depth="0.1" height="1" width="2" color="#8B4513"></a-box>
        <a-box position="0 0.5 -5" depth="0.1" height="1" width="4" color="#8B4513"></a-box>

        <a-text value="Café" position="-2 1.5 -5" class="sign"></a-text>
        <a-text value="Kaffee" position="2 1.5 -5" class="sign"></a-text>
        <a-text value="Kahawa" position="0 1.5 -5" class="sign"></a-text>

        <a-text value="Menu" position="-2 2.5 -5" class="sign"></a-text>
        <a-text value="Speisekarte" position="2 2.5 -5" class="sign"></a-text>
        <a-text value="Menyu" position="0 2.5 -5" class="sign"></a-text>

        <a-text value="Open" position="-2 3.5 -5" class="sign"></a-text>
        <a-text value="Geöffnet" position="2 3.5 -5" class="sign"></a-text>
        <a-text value="Fungua" position="0 3.5 -5" class="sign"></a-text>

        <a-text value="Welcome" position="-2 4.5 -5" class="sign"></a-text>
        <a-text value="Willkommen" position="2 4.5 -5" class="sign"></a-text>
        <a-text value="Karibu" position="0 4.5 -5" class="sign"></a-text>

        <a-camera id="camera" position="0 1.6 0">
            <a-cursor></a-cursor>
        </a-camera>
    </a-scene>

    <script>
        document.addEventListener('keydown', function(event) {
            const camera = document.getElementById('camera');
            const position = camera.getAttribute('position');

            switch(event.key) {
                case 'ArrowUp':
                    camera.setAttribute('position', {x: position.x, y: position.y, z: position.z - 0.1});
                    break;
                case 'ArrowDown':
                    camera.setAttribute('position', {x: position.x, y: position.y, z: position.z + 0.1});
                    break;
                case 'ArrowLeft':
                    camera.setAttribute('position', {x: position.x - 0.1, y: position.y, z: position.z});
                    break;
                case 'ArrowRight':
                    camera.setAttribute('position', {x: position.x + 0.1, y: position.y, z: position.z});
                    break;
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions:
1. Copy the code above.
2. Paste it into a text editor and save it as `index.html`.
3. Open the `index.html` file in a web browser that supports A-Frame and WebVR (like Chrome or Firefox).
4. Use the arrow keys to navigate around the scene. 

This code creates a simple VR environment with signs in three languages, allowing for basic navigation. You can expand upon this by adding more features or enhancing the visual elements.
